Question Text: Given the following URI https://courses.examsdigest.com/ccna, which part is the hostname?
Choices:
a. https
b. courses
c. courses.examsdigest.com
d. examsdigest.com
e. examsdigest.com/ccna
LLM Explanation: In the given URI 'https://courses.examsdigest.com/ccna', the hostname part is 'courses.examsdigest.com'. The hostname is the part of a URI that identifies the domain to which the resource is hosted.

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 443?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure) uses port 443 for secure communication over a computer network. It is the secure version of HTTP, providing encrypted communication.

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 80?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) uses port 80 for communication. It is the protocol used for transferring hypertext requests and information on the World Wide Web.

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 25?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) uses port 25 for communication. It is the standard protocol for sending emails between servers.

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 22?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SSH (Secure Shell) uses port 22 for secure remote access to devices. It provides a secure channel over an unsecured network by using encryption. Port 22 is the default port for SSH traffic.

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the SNMP protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: The SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol) primarily uses UDP port 161 for communication between the manager and the agent. This port is used for sending requests from the manager to the agent and receiving responses from the agent to the manager.

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the POP3 protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: The correct port number for the POP3 protocol is 110. POP3 (Post Office Protocol version 3) is used for receiving emails from a remote server to a local email client. It operates over TCP port 110.

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the DNS protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: DNS (Domain Name System) protocol uses port number 53 for both TCP and UDP communications. Port 53 is the well-known port assigned for DNS.

Question Text: Which of the following options are things that a standard IP ACL could be configured to do? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. Match the exact source IP address
b. Match all IP addresses in a subnet with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
c. Match IP addresses 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
d. Match only the packet’s destination IP address
LLM Explanation: A standard IP ACL can be configured to match the exact source IP address (option a) by specifying the specific IP address to permit or deny. It can also match all IP addresses in a subnet with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses (option b) by using the subnet mask to define the range of IP addresses to permit or deny.

Question Text: One of the differences between named and numbered ACLs is that named ACLS using ACL subcommands, not global commands, to define the action and matching parameters.
Choices:
a. TRUE
b. FALSE
LLM Explanation: The statement is TRUE. Named ACLs use ACL subcommands to define the action and matching parameters, unlike numbered ACLs that use global commands. Named ACLs provide more flexibility and ease of management compared to numbered ACLs.

Question Text: Given the following fields, which of those cannot be compared on an extended IP ACL?
Choices:
a. Application protocol
b. Destination IP address
c. Source IP address
d. URL
e. TOS Byte
LLM Explanation: The fields that cannot be compared on an extended IP ACL are Application protocol (a) and URL (d). Extended IP ACLs operate at the network layer (Layer 3) of the OSI model and can filter traffic based on criteria such as source and destination IP addresses, TOS Byte, and sometimes port numbers. Application protocols and URLs are typically filtered using higher-layer protocols like Layer 4 (transport layer) or Layer 7 (application layer) protocols, not by IP ACLs.

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #1: Permit packets from 186.33.2.3
ACL command #1: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3
b. access-list 1 deny 186.33.2.3
c. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.0
d. access-list 1 deny 186.33.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct ACL command to permit packets from the specific IP address 186.33.2.3 is 'access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3'. This command allows traffic from that exact IP address.

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #2: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets
ACL command #2: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 1 permit 57.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 deny 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct ACL command to permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets is 'access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255'. This command matches the specified criteria by allowing any IP address where the first three octets are 56.57.2.

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #3: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets
ACL command #3: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255
b. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.255.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.58.0.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct ACL command to permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets is 'access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255'. This command allows any IP address where the first two octets are 56.57.

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #4: Permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5, sent to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24
ACL command #4: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq 23
b. access-list 101 permit any any
c. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
d. access-list 101 deny tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
LLM Explanation: The correct ACL command to permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5 to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24 is 'access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www'. This command allows TCP traffic from the specified source IP to the destination subnet with the destination port set to 'www' (port 80 for HTTP).

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #5: Permit any and every IPv4 packet
ACL command #5: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit ip any any
b. access-list 101 deny ip any any
c. access-list 101 permit ip 0.0.0.0 any
d. access-list 101 permit ip any 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct ACL command to permit any and every IPv4 packet is 'access-list 101 permit ip any any'. This statement allows all IPv4 traffic to pass through the ACL.

Question Text: Which of the following commands display the configuration of an IPv4 ACL, including line numbers? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. show running-config
b. show startup-config
c. show ip access-lists
d. show access-lists
LLM Explanation: Option C and D are correct. 'show ip access-lists' and 'show access-lists' commands display the configuration of an IPv4 ACL, including line numbers. These commands provide visibility into the access control lists configured on the device along with their line numbers for easy reference and troubleshooting.

Question Text: Type the access-list command that permits all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24. Use the ACL number 50 for the ACL rule.
Choices:
a. access-list 50 permit 14.15.17.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 50 deny 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.255.255.255
d. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24 using ACL number 50 is 'access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255'. This command allows all IP addresses from 14.15.16.0 to 14.15.16.255.

Question Text: Given the following access-list command access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255, choose the exact range of IP addresses, matched by the command.
LLM Explanation: The access-list command 'access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255' with wildcard bits 0.0.0.255 translates to a range from 192.168.4.0 to 192.168.4.255. The wildcard mask 0.0.0.255 means that the last octet is a range from 0 to 255, allowing all IP addresses in the subnet 192.168.4.0/24 to be matched by this command.

Question Text: The range of valid ACL numbers for standard numbered IP ACLs is:
LLM Explanation: The range of valid ACL numbers for standard numbered IP ACLs is 1-99 and 1300-1999. Standard numbered IP ACLs use numbers from 1 to 99 and from 1300 to 1999.

Question Text:
The ACL 55 on R1 has four statements, in the following order, with address and wildcard mask values as follows:
1. 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255
2. 20.20.0.0 0.0.255.255
3. 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255
4. 2.2.2.0 0.0.0.255
If a router tried to match a packet sourced from IP address 20.20.20.20 using this ACL, which ACL statement does a router consider the packet to have matched?
Choices:
a. First statement
b. Second statement
c. Third statement
d. Forth statement
e. Implied deny at the end of the ACL
LLM Explanation: The router matches the packet against the ACL statements in sequential order. When a packet's source IP address is 20.20.20.20, it will match the third statement in the ACL, which specifies the range 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255.

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3 and a destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 28
b. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny tcp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 25 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access-list command to deny packets meeting the specified criteria is 'access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25'. This command denies UDP packets from any source IP with a source port greater than 10455, destined for IP address 30.3.3.3 with a destination port equal to 25.

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, a source IP address 30.3.3.3 and a source port greater than 10455, any destination IP address 30.3.3.3 with destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 30
b. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 25 any eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.0.0.0 gt 10455 any eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access-list statement to deny packets with the specified conditions is option d. It denies UDP packets with a source IP address of 30.3.3.3, a source port greater than 10455, any destination IP address, and a destination port equal to 25.

Question Text: Choose the wildcard mask that matches all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0, and mask 255.255.255.0.
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask is used in access control lists (ACLs) to identify the range of IP addresses. To match all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0 with a subnet mask of 255.255.255.0, the corresponding wildcard mask would be the inverse of the subnet mask. In this case, the correct wildcard mask is 0.255.255.255.
